Done. The week view now has a per-day project summary band pinned between the day-name header and the scrolling timeline, so it's always visible on first load without scrolling.

What I built

- A new `DaySummaryView` (in `Sources/BarTimeTracker/WeekTimelineWindow.swift`) that sits above the scrollable timeline.
- For each day it reuses `TimeCalculations.dailyProjectTotals` (which already excludes `Break`), filters out internal `~logged out~`/`~resumed~` entries, and renders:
  - One colored pill per project — colors match the existing timeline palette (`projectColor`), so each row reads as the same project you see in the grid below.
  - Project name on the left, decimal hours on the right (`%.2f`, e.g. `2.50`, `6.75`) in monospaced digits so the column lines up.
  - A bold grand-total line per day at the bottom (`6.75h`), tinted with the system accent color for today.
  - A dim `—` for empty days.
  - `+N more · X.XXh` overflow indicator if a day has too many projects to fit (still gives you the remaining sum for reporting).

Layout cleverness

- The summary band auto-sizes each reload to fit the tallest day of the visible week, clamped to `[72, 220]` pt, then pushes the timeline scroll view down accordingly. So simple weeks stay compact; busy weeks expand just enough.
- Today's column gets the same subtle accent tint used in the timeline, keeping visual continuity.
- `autoresizingMask` keeps the band pinned to the top on window resize; the timeline below fills the rest.

